Review of renderHTML()

Code
--------------------------------------------------------------------
function renderHTML(userInput) {
  document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = userInput;
}

Problems
====================================================================
1. DOM-based Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
   • Whatever the caller passes in is written straight to innerHTML.  
     A payload such as  <img src=x onerror="alert(document.cookie)">  
     will execute immediately.

2. Missing element-existence check  
   • If no element whose id is "output" exists,   
     document.getElementById('output') returns null and the next line
     throws “Cannot set property ‘innerHTML’ of null”.

3. Tight coupling / global pollution  
   • Hard-codes the target element id and leaves renderHTML as a
     global function.  This makes unit-testing and reuse harder.

4. No type validation  
   • Non-string values will be implicitly converted; passing an object
     could produce “[object Object]”, or, worse, a function that is
     converted to its source code and rendered.

5. Minor performance issue  
   • innerHTML causes the browser to parse the whole HTML fragment and
     re-create DOM nodes every time.  If you only need text, this is
     unnecessary work.

How to fix / improve
====================================================================
A. Eliminate XSS
   1. If you only need to display plain text, never use innerHTML.
      function renderText(userInput) {
        const el = document.getElementById('output');
        if (!el) return;                       // fail-soft
        el.textContent = String(userInput);    // auto-escapes
      }

   2. If you must allow limited markup (e.g. <b>, <i>):  
      • Sanitize first with a well-maintained library such as DOMPurify.

      import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';
      function renderHTML(userInput) {
        const el = document.getElementById('output');
        if (!el) return;
        el.innerHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(String(userInput), {
          ALLOWED_TAGS: ['b','i','strong','em','br']
        });
      }

   3. Add a Content-Security-Policy header on the server to further
      mitigate XSS (e.g. disallow inline scripts, restrict img src).

B. Handle missing element safely
   const el = document.getElementById('output');
   if (!el) {
     console.warn('#output not found');
     return;
   }

C. API design / encapsulation
   • Pass the target element (or selector) as a parameter:

     export function renderHTML(container, html) {
       if (!(container instanceof HTMLElement)) {
         throw new TypeError('container must be an HTMLElement');
       }
       container.innerHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(String(html));
     }

D. Validation / typing
   • Force the input to a string with String(userInput) or template-
     literal `${userInput}` before inserting.

E. Performance
   • If you repeatedly update only a tiny part, prefer textContent
     or createElement/appendChild rather than replacing innerHTML
     wholesale.

Checklist after refactor
--------------------------------------------------------------------
[ ] All untrusted data is escaped or sanitized before being injected.  
[ ] Function fails gracefully if the DOM node is missing.  
[ ] No global name collisions; the function is exported/scoped.  
[ ] Optional: CSP enabled server-side, unit tests for sanitizer rules,  
    TypeScript or JSDoc annotations for stronger typing.
